<subSubSection id="8FCC6574FF8A3428FF5907E7FA12D371" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C76936FFFF8A3428FF5907E7FEE9D331" blockId="4.[192,1440,643,860]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="F5A2EAEDFF8A3428FF5907E7FE04D2B1" bold="true" box="[192,317,643,667]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Remarks</emphasis>
. This is a remarkably distinctive species that goes to couplet 
<quantity id="002E9B1AFF8A3428FBB107E7FB5CD2B1" box="[1064,1125,643,667]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.906" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" unit="in" value="39.0">39 in</quantity>
the species key of 
<bibRefCitation id="A3474B0EFF8A3428FADD07E7FE8ED291" author="Gordon, R. D. &amp; C. Canepari" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="245 - 512" refId="ref7630" refString="Gordon, R. D., and C. Canepari. 2008. South American Coccinellidae (Coleoptera), Part XI: a systematic revision of Hyperaspidini (Hyperaspidinae). Annali del Museo Civico di Storia Naturale &quot; G. Doria &quot; XCIX: 245 - 512." type="book chapter" year="2008">Gordon and Canepari (2008)</bibRefCitation>
, but has nothing in common with the two species in that couplet. Characters that set 
<taxonomicName id="00D64D7CFF8A3428FF5907A0FE58D2F1" authorityName="Gordon &amp; González" authorityYear="2011" box="[192,353,707,731]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Hyperaspis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="divaricata">
<emphasis id="F5A2EAEDFF8A3428FF5907A0FFEFD2F1" box="[192,214,708,731]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5A2EAEDFF8A3428FF7A07A7FE58D2F1" box="[227,353,707,731]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">divaricata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
apart from all presently known 
<taxonomicName id="00D64D7CFF8A3428FD7D07A0FCF2D2F1" box="[740,971,707,731]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Hyperaspis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="F5A2EAEDFF8A3428FD7D07A0FC57D2F1" box="[740,878,708,731]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Hyperaspis</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
are: large size and round, convex form; elytral color pattern with 5 spots, median spot on apical declivity orange; distinctly flanged protibia; and form of male genitalia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C76936FFFF8A3428FF690647FA12D371" blockId="4.[192,1440,643,860]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
The dorsal habitus is reminiscent of some North American 
<taxonomicName id="00D64D7CFF8A3428FC280640FB03D311" authorityName="Chevrolat" authorityYear="1836" box="[945,1082,804,827]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Hyperaspis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F5A2EAEDFF8A3428FC280640FB03D311" box="[945,1082,804,827]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Hyperaspis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taxa, particularly 
<taxonomicName id="00D64D7CFF8A3428FA810640FE11D371" authority="Mulsant" authorityName="Mulsant" authorityYear="1850" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Hyperaspis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lateralis">
<emphasis id="F5A2EAEDFF8A3428FA810640FA17D311" box="[1304,1326,804,827]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5A2EAEDFF8A3428FAA20647FA99D311" box="[1339,1440,803,827]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">lateralis</emphasis>
Mulsant
</taxonomicName>
, which is also a large, multispotted species often with one spot red or orange in color.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8FCC6574FF8A3428FF5906E7FE53D391" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="C76936FFFF8A3428FF5906E7FE53D391" blockId="4.[192,1440,899,955]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="F5A2EAEDFF8A3428FF5906E7FE6AD3B1" bold="true" box="[192,339,899,923]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Etymology</emphasis>
. The species name is from the Latin 
<emphasis id="F5A2EAEDFF8A3428FC9F06E7FCA9D3B1" box="[774,912,899,923]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">divaricatus</emphasis>
in reference to the distinctive appearance of 
<taxonomicName id="00D64D7CFF8A3428FF5906C0FE5AD391" authorityName="Gordon &amp; González" authorityYear="2011" box="[192,355,931,955]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Hyperaspis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="divaricata">
<emphasis id="F5A2EAEDFF8A3428FF5906C0FFEFD391" box="[192,214,932,955]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="F5A2EAEDFF8A3428FF7D06C7FE5AD391" box="[228,355,931,955]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">divaricata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
